    // 1. Baguio weekend in summer
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2020/05/things-to-do-in-baguio-travel-guide-itinerary.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Baguio in Summer: A Weekend That Skips the Long-Weekend Madness',
        'slug' => 'baguio-summer-weekend-skip-long-weekend-madness',
        'excerpt' => 'Summer in Baguio still works if you plan around the crowds, not against them. Here is a calm two-night weekend that gets you in before sunrise and out before the Sunday jam.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Baguio in March, April, and early May is the version most Filipinos remember from childhood. Pine air, strawberry taho mornings, and that 18-degree breeze that makes a hoodie feel right at sunset. The catch is everyone else remembers the same thing, so the summer Baguio trip lives or dies on timing. The fix is to arrive on a Friday before sunrise, sleep slightly outside Session Road, and roll back to Manila on a Sunday before lunch.</p><p>This plan assumes two nights, a Cubao bus ride up, and a small group of two to four. Tara, here is the route.</p><h2>Friday: Arrive at Dawn, Eat at the Market</h2><p>Take the late-night <a href="https://www.victoryliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Victory Liner</a> trip from Cubao or Pasay around 11 p.m. so you roll into Baguio terminal by 4 to 5 a.m. The deluxe service runs PHP 750 to PHP 850 and skips most stops, while the regular aircon at PHP 450 to PHP 600 gets you there with a few more breaks. Either way, you land before the sun and the city is quiet.</p><h3>Breakfast at the Public Market</h3><p>Walk or Grab to Baguio Public Market. The carinderias inside open by 5 a.m. Order longganisa, garlic rice, and a cup of brewed Benguet coffee. Vendors will already be assembling strawberry taho cups out front. Eat slow, the rest of the day depends on you not rushing.</p><h3>Burnham Park, Then Drop Bags</h3><p>Burnham Park is at its best before 9 a.m. Rent a swan boat or just walk the loop. By 10 a.m., check into your hotel or pension house. Sleep two hours if your eyes are heavy. The afternoon is the real day.</p><h2>Saturday: The Classic Loop, Done Backwards</h2><p>Most tour groups do Mines View, Mansion, and Wright Park in the morning, which means the buses arrive by 8 a.m. Flip the order. Hit BenCab Museum in Tuba first while everyone else is queueing at Mines View. BenCab opens at 9 a.m. and the museum cafe makes a calm two-hour stop. Drive back into the city by lunch.</p><h3>Mansion, Wright, Mines View at Sunset</h3><p>Reach Mansion House and Wright Park by 3 p.m., when the tour buses have already cleared. The horseback row at Wright Park costs around PHP 400 to PHP 500 for a short loop. Roll into Mines View by 5 p.m. for sunset, when the souvenir stalls are packing up and the light hits the valley well.</p><h3>Dinner at Camp John Hay or Hill Station</h3><p>Camp John Hay has Le Chef and the row of pine-shaded restaurants near The Manor. Hill Station near Casa Vallejo is the calmer pick for two people. Reservation helps on a Saturday.</p><h2>Sunday: Slow Morning, Early Exit</h2><p>The Sunday move is to sleep in, walk to Choco-Late de Batirol or Cafe by the Ruins for a long breakfast, and roll back to Manila by 11 a.m. The afternoon Marcos Highway jam starts by 2 p.m. and lasts until midnight on a long weekend.</p><h3>Pasalubong Run</h3><ul><li>Strawberry jam and ube jam at Good Shepherd, queue starts by 9 a.m.</li><li>Walis tambo and woven baskets at the public market</li><li>Brewed Benguet coffee beans, ground or whole, at any market stall</li><li>Choco-Late de Batirol tablea for hot chocolate at home</li></ul><h2>Where to Sleep</h2><p>Stay around Leonard Wood Road, Outlook Drive, or upper Session if you want quiet. Avoid hotels right on Session Road during summer because the traffic noise carries through the night. For comparing pension houses and small hotels, you can cross-check options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g294263-Baguio_Benguet_Province_Cordillera_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p><p>Baguio in summer still rewards travelers who move early and eat at the market. The pine smell does not change, only the crowd patterns do.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2020/05/things-to-do-in-baguio-travel-guide-itinerary.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Pinoy Adventurista</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Baguio Summer Weekend Plan: Skip the Crowds | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm two-night Baguio summer plan with pre-dawn arrival, market breakfast, the classic loop done backwards, and an early Sunday exit.',
