    // 2. Baguio rainy season cafe hopping
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://baguiotransient.net/guides/baguio-rainy-season-guide',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Baguio Transient',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Baguio in the Rainy Season: A Two-Day Cafe Crawl That Works',
        'slug' => 'baguio-rainy-season-cafe-crawl-two-days',
        'excerpt' => 'June to October in Baguio is the version no one tells you about. Cool, foggy, and almost empty. Here is a calm two-day cafe hopping plan for the rainy months.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Most Filipinos visit Baguio between December and May, which means June to October has the city almost to itself. Yes, it rains. Yes, the fog rolls into Session Road by 4 p.m. and stays. That is the appeal. The pine smell is stronger after a downpour, the cafes feel warmer, and you can finally get a window seat at Cafe by the Ruins on a Saturday afternoon.</p><p>This two-day plan assumes you ride up on a Friday night and head back Sunday afternoon. Pack a light raincoat, dry socks, and a book.</p><h2>Day 1: Long Coffees, Short Walks</h2><p>Take a <a href="https://www.victoryliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Victory Liner</a> trip from Cubao at 10 or 11 p.m., arriving by 4 to 5 a.m. The fare runs PHP 450 to PHP 850 depending on whether you pick regular or deluxe. Drop your bags, sleep two hours, then start the day late. The rainy-season Baguio is for slow movers.</p><h3>Mid-Morning at Cafe by the Ruins</h3><p>Cafe by the Ruins along Chuntug is the right opener. The semi-open dining room lets you hear the rain on the roof while staying dry. Order bibingka with kesong puti, brewed Benguet coffee, and the camote bread. Stay two hours. This is not a stop, it is the morning.</p><h3>Afternoon: Mt. Cloud and Arca\'s Yard</h3><p>Walk to Mt. Cloud Bookshop near Casa Vallejo. It is small, quiet, and stacks Cordillera-published titles you will not find in Manila. Buy one book. Take a Grab to Arca\'s Yard in Ambuklao Road for the afternoon. The cafe is built around a private library, and the rain outside makes the wood interior smell like a different city.</p><h3>Dinner: Hill Station or Oh My Gulay</h3><p>For dinner, pick one. Hill Station is the warm sit-down with the proper menu. Oh My Gulay above La Azotea on Session is the vegetarian space run by artist Kidlat Tahimik, all wood and salvaged glass. Both feel right in a downpour.</p><h2>Day 2: BenCab in the Fog, Then Choco-Late</h2><p>BenCab Museum in Tuba is the rainy-season anchor. The drive out feels slower in the fog, and the museum interior is built around skylights that let in the muted gray. The garden cafe overlooks a small ravine that disappears into the mist by 2 p.m. Spend three hours here easy.</p><h3>Afternoon: Choco-Late de Batirol</h3><p>Head to Choco-Late de Batirol inside Camp John Hay for the closing cup. The cafe is open-air but covered, with a fire pit in the middle. Order the classic tablea hot chocolate, the camote chips, and the suman. The pine surrounding the deck is where Baguio earns its name in the rain.</p><h3>Other Wet-Weather Stops</h3><ul><li>Cafe Voltaire near Outlook Drive for craft coffee and a quiet upstairs</li><li>Vizco\'s for strawberry shortcake and a window seat</li><li>Hatch Coffee inside La Azotea for the local roast</li><li>Agara Ramen if you want a hot bowl instead of cake</li></ul><h2>What to Pack for Rainy Baguio</h2><ul><li>A proper raincoat, not just an umbrella, the wind on Outlook Drive is unkind</li><li>Two pairs of dry socks per day</li><li>Closed shoes with grip, sidewalks get slippery</li><li>A book, a journal, or your laptop, the cafes are made for sitting</li></ul><p>For pension houses and small hotels around the city, you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g294263-Baguio_Benguet_Province_Cordillera_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. The rainy season is the cheapest window to book Baguio.</p><p>Rainy Baguio is the version you go back to when you outgrow the long-weekend rush. Slow coffees, foggy walks, and one good book.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://baguiotransient.net/guides/baguio-rainy-season-guide" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Baguio Transient</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Baguio Rainy Season Cafe Crawl: 2-Day Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm two-day rainy-season Baguio plan with Cafe by the Ruins, BenCab in the fog, Arca\'s Yard, and Choco-Late de Batirol. Quieter, cheaper, slower.',
        'tags' => 'Baguio, rainy season, cafes, Cordillera, weekend',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'la-union',
    ],

    // 3. Sagada hike + Echo Valley
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.raescape.com/2017/12/cordillera-sagada.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'RaEscape',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Sagada and the Echo Valley Hike: A Slow Two-Day Plan',
        'slug' => 'sagada-echo-valley-hike-two-day-plan',
        'excerpt' => 'Sagada works as a two-night trip if you build it around one good hike, one slow morning, and a long bus ride home. Here is the calm plan for first timers.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Sagada is one of those Cordillera towns where the trip is half the experience. You spend a night on a bus, a morning on a winding mountain road, and by the time you check into your inn the air is already thinner and the day is half gone. That is fine. Sagada is not a rush.</p><p>This two-night plan assumes you leave Manila on a Friday night, hike Echo Valley on Saturday, and bus back on Sunday. The Coda Lines route from Cubao is the direct one, running PHP 750 to PHP 900 for the 11 to 12-hour overnight trip.</p><h2>Day 1: Arrive, Register, Eat</h2><p>Coda Lines arrives in Sagada by mid to late morning. First stop is the Sagada Tourism Office for the environmental fee, which runs around PHP 100. Pick up your map and pre-book your guide for the next morning. Guides are required for the Echo Valley and Hanging Coffins walk, and the standard fee is around PHP 300 to PHP 600 split across the group.</p><h3>Lunch at Yoghurt House or Salt and Pepper</h3><p>Yoghurt House is the long-running stop for fresh yogurt with granola and a proper breakfast plate. Salt and Pepper Diner does the heavier Filipino menu. Either one is a 20-minute walk from the tourism office.</p><h3>Afternoon: Slow Walk to Sumaguing Entrance</h3><p>Day one is for getting your legs used to the elevation. Walk from town toward the Sumaguing Cave entrance, just to see the trailhead and the rice fields on the way. No need to enter the cave today. Save the energy.</p><h2>Day 2: Echo Valley at Sunrise</h2><p>Echo Valley is the hike most first-timers do, and the smart move is to start by 6 a.m. before the day groups arrive from their van trips. Meet your guide at the Episcopal Church of Saint Mary the Virgin. The walk passes through the church cemetery, down a stone staircase, and into the valley itself.</p><h3>The Hanging Coffins Viewpoint</h3><p>The Hanging Coffins viewpoint is around 30 minutes in. The coffins are nailed to a limestone cliff above the valley floor, a burial tradition of the Igorot people that goes back centuries. Stand at the viewpoint, take a quiet photo, do not climb up. The guide will explain the practice and you should listen because the local context matters more than the photo.</p><h3>The Loop Back</h3><p>The full loop takes around 2 to 3 hours including the cemetery, the valley floor, and the climb back up. You can extend it into the Bomod-ok Falls trail if your legs feel good, but most first-timers cap it at Echo Valley.</p><h2>Afternoon: Lemon Pie House and a Slow Sit</h2><p>After the hike, walk to Lemon Pie House for the namesake slice, an egg-white meringue on a soft crust. Sit on the porch. The afternoon is for rest, not another tour. If you want one more easy stop, Sagada Pottery is 10 minutes from town and lets you watch the potter at the wheel.</p><h3>Dinner at Misty Lodge or Log Cabin</h3><p>Log Cabin is the long-standing dinner spot, but reservation is needed. Misty Lodge is the calmer pick if you walked in late.</p><h2>Day 3: Sunrise at Kiltepan, Then Home</h2><p>Sunrise at Kiltepan Viewpoint is the closer most travelers do. Hire a tricycle by 4:30 a.m., fare around PHP 250 to PHP 350 round trip. The sea of clouds is not guaranteed, but the view of the rice terraces below is worth the early call. Be back in town by 7 a.m. for breakfast, then catch the morning Coda Lines bus back to Manila.</p><h3>What to Pack</h3><ul><li>Light jacket, the dawn at Kiltepan dips below 15 degrees</li><li>Trail shoes with grip, the Echo Valley stairs get slippery</li><li>Cash, no reliable ATMs in town</li><li>A reusable bottle, refill at your inn</li><li>Eye drops for the dust on the bus ride</li></ul><p>For inns and homestays in town, compare listings on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g778420-Sagada_Mountain_Province_Cordillera_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Most are walking distance from the tourism office.</p><p>Sagada rewards slow travelers. One hike, one viewpoint, one lemon pie. That is the trip.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://www.raescape.com/2017/12/cordillera-sagada.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">RaEscape</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Sagada Echo Valley Hike: 2-Day DIY Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm two-night Sagada plan covering Echo Valley, the Hanging Coffins, Kiltepan sunrise, and where to eat. Built for first timers who want to move slow.',
        'tags' => 'Sagada, Echo Valley, Cordillera, hiking, DIY',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'la-union',
    ],

    // 4. Banaue + Batad rice terraces
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://joansfootprints.com/2020/03/03/batad-banaue-diy-travel-guide-2020-budget-itinerary/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Joan\'s Footprints',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Banaue and Batad: A Three-Day DIY Plan for the Rice Terraces',
        'slug' => 'banaue-batad-three-day-diy-rice-terraces',
        'excerpt' => 'Banaue gets the postcards but Batad earns the trip. Here is a calm three-day plan that splits a night in each so you actually walk the amphitheater.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Banaue is the photo most Filipinos grew up seeing on the back of the 1000-peso bill, but the real Ifugao moment happens an hour deeper at Batad. The amphitheater of stone-walled terraces is only reachable on foot from the Saddle Point, and a night in the village changes the trip from a drive-by to a proper visit.</p><p>This three-day plan assumes you leave Manila on a Friday night, sleep one night in Banaue, one night in Batad, and bus back Monday morning. Ohayami Trans from Manila to Banaue is the direct overnight, running PHP 700 to PHP 1,000 for the 9 to 10-hour trip.</p><h2>Day 1: Saturday in Banaue</h2><p>Ohayami arrives in Banaue by 7 a.m. First stop is the tourism office for the environmental fee, around PHP 50, and to confirm your jeepney to Batad Saddle Point for the next day. Drop your bags at a Banaue inn near the public market.</p><h3>The Banaue Viewpoint Loop</h3><p>Hire a tricycle for the standard viewpoint tour, which covers the main Banaue Viewpoint, the Hiwang Native Village, the Tam-An Village, and a small museum. Tricycle fare for the half-day loop runs around PHP 500 to PHP 800 split across the group. The main viewpoint has the souvenir row and the Ifugao locals in traditional dress who pose for a small tip.</p><h3>Lunch and Slow Afternoon</h3><p>Eat at People\'s Lodge or Las Vegas Lodge along the main road. The pinikpikan and Ifugao rice are the order. Spend the afternoon resting because tomorrow involves a steep walk down to Batad.</p><h2>Day 2: Sunday in Batad</h2><p>The shared jeepney from Banaue to Batad Saddle Point leaves around 9 a.m. and again at 3 p.m. on most days. Fare is around PHP 150 to PHP 200 per person, or you can charter the whole jeep for PHP 1,500 to PHP 2,000 split across your group. The ride takes around an hour on a winding mountain road that gets rough near the end.</p><h3>The Walk Down to the Village</h3><p>From the Saddle Point, the walk down to Batad village takes 20 to 40 minutes, depending on your pace. The trail is well-marked stone steps. Bring only what you need for one night, leave the heavy bag at your Banaue inn. Most Batad inns are family-run, sitting on the terraces themselves with a balcony view of the amphitheater.</p><h3>Tappiya Falls Side Trip</h3><p>If your knees are up to it, hire a local guide at the village for the Tappiya Falls walk. The trail crosses the rice paddies and descends into the next valley. Round trip takes around 3 hours, and the waterfall pool is cold but swimmable. Guide fee is around PHP 400 to PHP 600. Pack water and a dry shirt.</p><h3>Sunset on the Amphitheater</h3><p>The amphitheater faces east, so sunset paints the rice walls in warm light from behind you. Sit on your inn balcony, order the local rice wine called tapuy if you want, and watch the village wind down. There is no cell signal in most parts of Batad. Treat it as the feature.</p><h2>Day 3: Monday Climb and Bus Home</h2><p>Wake at 5 a.m. for sunrise, then breakfast, then the climb back to the Saddle Point by 8 a.m. The walk up is harder than the walk down. Take your time and stop for water. Catch the morning jeepney back to Banaue, then the Ohayami evening bus back to Manila. You will land in Cubao by sunrise on Tuesday.</p><h3>What to Pack</h3><ul><li>Trail shoes with proper grip, not slippers</li><li>A small day pack for the Batad overnight, leave the rest in Banaue</li><li>Cash, no ATMs in Batad and limited ones in Banaue</li><li>A light jacket, mountain mornings dip cold</li><li>A flashlight or headlamp, the Batad village has limited power at night</li></ul><h2>Getting In and Out</h2><p>The most reliable overnight is Ohayami Trans from Cubao. <a href="https://www.victoryliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Victory Liner</a> runs Manila to Solano, from where you can take a van to Banaue, but the Ohayami direct route saves a transfer. Coda Lines also runs a Banaue trip.</p><p>For Banaue inns and Batad guesthouses, you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g644033-Banaue_Ifugao_Province_Cordillera_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Stay near the main road in Banaue for the early jeepney, and in the upper village in Batad for the amphitheater view.</p><p>Banaue is the photo. Batad is the trip. Do both, sleep in the village, and you will leave with the right memory.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://joansfootprints.com/2020/03/03/batad-banaue-diy-travel-guide-2020-budget-itinerary/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Joan\'s Footprints</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Banaue and Batad 3-Day DIY Rice Terraces Guide | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm three-day Banaue and Batad plan with the classic viewpoint loop, a night in the amphitheater village, and the Tappiya Falls side trip.',
        'tags' => 'Banaue, Batad, Ifugao, rice terraces, DIY',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'la-union',
    ],

    // 5. La Union surf weekend (Urbiztondo)
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2021/08/things-to-do-in-la-union-tourist-spots-itinerary.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'La Union Surf Weekend: An Urbiztondo Plan for First Timers',
        'slug' => 'la-union-surf-weekend-urbiztondo-first-timers',
        'excerpt' => 'San Juan, La Union is the easiest surf weekend from Manila. Here is a calm two-night plan with a beginner lesson, a sunset, and a slow Sunday before the bus home.',
        'content_html' => '<p>La Union is the surf weekend most Manila kids take when they want salt water without flying. The drive is around 5 to 7 hours, the waves are forgiving for beginners, and the strip along Urbiztondo Beach in San Juan has enough cafes and surf shops that you can plan a weekend without booking a tour.</p><p>This two-night plan assumes a Friday night bus, a Saturday lesson, and a Sunday lunch before heading back. The surf season runs roughly October to March, but smaller, beginner-friendly waves break the rest of the year too.</p><h2>Friday: The Overnight Bus Up</h2><p>Take the late-night <a href="https://www.partas.com.ph" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Partas</a> or <a href="https://www.victoryliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Victory Liner</a> trip from Cubao or Pasay, bound for San Fernando, La Union. Fare runs PHP 500 to PHP 750 for regular aircon, more for the deluxe. Tell the conductor to drop you at the San Juan junction. From there, a tricycle to Urbiztondo runs PHP 50 to PHP 100. You will arrive by 4 to 5 a.m., which is the right hour to walk to the beach and watch the sky turn.</p><h3>Sleep, Then Late Breakfast</h3><p>Drop your bags at your surf hostel. Sleep until 8 a.m. Breakfast at El Union Coffee for a long latte and a tartine, or at Clean Beach Cafe for the longer Filipino plate. Both are on the Urbiztondo strip and walking distance from most hostels.</p><h2>Saturday: First Lesson, Sunset Paddle</h2><p>Surf lessons run all along the Urbiztondo beachfront. Standard rate is PHP 400 per hour with a board, instructor included. Book the morning slot at 6 to 7 a.m. when the wind is gentlest and the beachbreak is most forgiving for first-timers. Two hours is plenty for the first day. You will stand up, you will fall down, and you will eat a real lunch after.</p><h3>Lunch and Long Nap</h3><p>Make Coffee at Masa for the post-surf reset. Order the avocado toast and the cold brew. After lunch, sleep through the heat. Real surfers nap. Imitate them.</p><h3>Afternoon Walk: Monaliza Point and the Strip</h3><p>By 3 p.m., walk the strip north toward Monaliza Point. The advanced surfers ride the reef break here, and watching them is part of the day. Stop at any of the small surf shops, pick up a wax bar or a leash for pasalubong, and circle back to the beachfront for sunset.</p><h3>Sunset and Dinner</h3><p>Urbiztondo sunset is the social hour. Bars like Flotsam and Jetsam, Sebay, and the smaller beachfront kiosks fill up by 5:30 p.m. Order a San Mig Light, sit on the sand, and let the day end. Dinner can wait until 8 p.m. when the beach crowd thins.</p><h2>Sunday: Last Paddle, Then Bus Home</h2><p>Sunday morning is for one more paddle session at dawn if your shoulders allow. Otherwise, sleep in, brunch at Tagpuan or Great Northwest Cafe, and pack out by noon. The afternoon Partas back to Manila runs PHP 500 to PHP 750. Buy your ticket the day before if it is a long weekend.</p><h3>What to Pack</h3><ul><li>Rashguard with sleeves, the morning sun burns fast</li><li>Reef-safe sunscreen with zinc oxide</li><li>Two pairs of shorts, one for the water, one for the cafe</li><li>A small dry bag for your phone</li><li>Cash for the surf instructor tip</li></ul><h2>Beyond the Surf</h2><p>If you have a third night, drive 30 minutes north to Bacnotan for the Tangadan Falls or south to Bauang for the grape farm side trip. Most weekenders stick to Urbiztondo, which is the right call for a first visit.</p><p>For hostels and small resorts along the Urbiztondo strip, you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g1391574-San_Juan_La_Union_Province_Ilocos_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Book early on long weekends because the strip sells out fast.</p><p>La Union is the calm surf weekend Manila keeps coming back to. One lesson, one sunset, one slow Sunday.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2021/08/things-to-do-in-la-union-tourist-spots-itinerary.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Pinoy Adventurista</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'La Union Surf Weekend at Urbiztondo: First Timer Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm two-night La Union surf weekend at Urbiztondo Beach. Beginner lesson, sunset bars, slow Sunday, and the bus route that works.',
        'tags' => 'La Union, Urbiztondo, surf, San Juan, weekend',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'la-union',
    ],

