    // 20. Anawangin Cove camping Zambales
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.thepoortraveler.net/2018/03/anawangin-cove/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Poor Traveler',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Anawangin Cove Camping: A DIY Two-Day Plan via Pundaquit',
        'slug' => 'anawangin-cove-camping-diy-two-day-pundaquit',
        'excerpt' => 'Anawangin Cove is the no-signal beach camp that introduced a generation of Filipinos to weekend backpacking. Here is the calm DIY plan via Pundaquit.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Anawangin Cove in San Antonio, Zambales is the curved gray-sand beach that earned a reputation in the late 2000s for being a Manila-accessible camping weekend. The cove is reached only by boat from Pundaquit or by a 3-hour mountain trek over Mount Pundaquit. Most travelers take the boat. Once on the cove, there is no signal, no power except small generators, and only a row of agoho pine trees fronting the open South China Sea.</p><p>This plan assumes a Saturday morning bus to Pundaquit, an overnight camp on the cove, and a Sunday afternoon back to Manila. Bus from Manila on <a href="https://www.victoryliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Victory Liner</a> Cubao to Iba route, alight at San Antonio, fare around PHP 350 to PHP 500. From San Antonio, a tricycle to Pundaquit beach runs PHP 50 to PHP 100.</p><h2>Saturday Morning: Get to Pundaquit</h2><p>Take the 4 a.m. Victory Liner bus from Cubao so you arrive in San Antonio by 8 to 9 a.m. From the San Antonio terminal, tricycle to Pundaquit beach takes 15 minutes. At Pundaquit, the boat operators line the shore and quote the round-trip rates.</p><h3>Boat Rates</h3><p>The standard boat to Anawangin runs PHP 1,500 to PHP 2,500 round trip, fitting up to 6 people. You can also book the longer island-hopping route that includes Capones Island and Camara Island for around PHP 2,500 to PHP 3,500. The boat drops you at the cove in the morning and picks you up at a scheduled time the next day. Confirm the pickup time before you board.</p><h3>Camping Fees</h3><p>At Anawangin Cove, you pay the environmental fee of around PHP 100 per person and a camping fee of around PHP 200 to PHP 300 for the night. Tent rental is available on-site for around PHP 300 to PHP 500. Bring your own if you have one.</p><h2>Saturday Afternoon: Settle and Swim</h2><p>Arrive at Anawangin by 10 a.m. Pitch your tent under the agoho pines that line the back of the cove. The shade is the main reason these trees were planted. Save your tent stakes if it is windy.</p><h3>Swim and Walk the Cove</h3><p>The water at Anawangin is calm in the dry season and rougher between July and October when the typhoon swell comes in. Swim, walk the full length of the cove which is around 1.5 kilometers of gray volcanic sand, and rest under the trees. There is a small lagoon at the back of the cove fed by a stream, worth a 15-minute walk.</p><h3>Lunch and Afternoon Nap</h3><p>The small carinderias at the back of the cove sell grilled fish, rice, and instant noodles. Prices are higher than mainland because everything is brought in by boat. Around PHP 150 to PHP 300 per plate. Or bring your own packed lunch from San Antonio.</p><h2>Saturday Evening: Sunset and Stars</h2><p>Sunset on Anawangin faces the open South China Sea so the light hits the cove in full warm orange. Sit on the sand, no agenda. After dinner, the night sky is the feature. With no city lights for 50 kilometers, the stars are visible in a way most Manila travelers have never seen.</p><h3>Optional: Hike Up Anawangin Peak</h3><p>The peak overlooking the cove is reachable by a 30-minute climb on a marked trail at the south end of the cove. Sunset from the peak is the standard photo. Bring a headlamp for the climb down.</p><h2>Sunday Morning: Capones Island Side Trip</h2><p>If your boat package includes the island-hopping loop, the morning is for Capones Island and Camara Island. Boat picks you up at 7 a.m. for the loop.</p><h3>Capones Island</h3><p>Capones Island has a Spanish-era lighthouse on the rocky upper section, built in 1890. The walk from the boat landing to the lighthouse takes around 30 minutes on a rough trail. The lighthouse interior is closed but the view from the base covers the whole western coast of Zambales. Stay 1 hour.</p><h3>Camara Island</h3><p>Camara Island is the smaller, calmer stop. The white-sand cove on the south side is good for a 30-minute swim. Lunch can be served here by your boat crew if you arranged it.</p><h2>Sunday Afternoon: Back to Pundaquit and Manila</h2><p>The boat brings you back to Pundaquit by 1 to 2 p.m. From Pundaquit, tricycle to San Antonio, then Victory Liner back to Cubao. The afternoon bus leaves every hour. Travel time back to Manila is 4 to 5 hours.</p><h3>What to Pack for the Camp</h3><ul><li>A tent and a sleeping bag or a lightweight blanket</li><li>A headlamp, the cove has no power at night</li><li>Reef-safe sunscreen and a hat for the day</li><li>A reusable bottle, refills are PHP 20 to PHP 50 at the cove stalls</li><li>Cash for everything, no signal means no GCash</li><li>A trash bag, all waste must be packed out</li><li>Bug spray for the agoho pine zone</li><li>A camp stove if you cook your own, no open fires allowed</li></ul><h2>Rules at Anawangin</h2><ul><li>No open fires on the sand or under the pines</li><li>Pack out all trash including biodegradable waste</li><li>No loud music after 10 p.m.</li><li>Stay on the marked trail to the peak</li><li>Do not pick the plants or take the rocks</li></ul><h2>Best Months to Camp</h2><p>The dry season runs November to May. December to February has the coolest evenings and the calmest water. March to May warms up but the cove is still swimmable. June to October is typhoon season, and the cove can be closed if a storm is in the area.</p><h2>Where to Sleep Before and After</h2><p>If you arrive in San Antonio late on a Friday and want to overnight before the boat, the inns along Pundaquit are basic but clean. For comparing options, you can cross-check on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g6781025-San_Antonio_Zambales_Province_Central_Luzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p><p>Anawangin Cove is the original Manila camping weekend that taught a generation of Filipinos to pack light and sleep under pines. One boat, one tent, one night without signal.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://www.thepoortraveler.net/2018/03/anawangin-cove/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">The Poor Traveler</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Anawangin Cove Camping DIY Plan via Pundaquit | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm two-day Anawangin Cove camping plan via Pundaquit. Boat rates, camping fees, the Capones Island side trip, and what to pack for the no-signal night.',
        'tags' => 'Anawangin, Zambales, Pundaquit, camping, beach',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'subic',
